 achieve these goals, that things are getting—or are on the verge of getting—worse. In American Nightmares, Best addresses the apprehension that we face every day as we are bombarded with threats that the social institutions we count on are imperiled. Our schools are failing to teach our kids. Healthcare may soon be harder to obtain. We can’t bank on our retirement plans. And our homes—still the largest chunk of most people’s net worth—may lose much of their value. Our very way of life is being threatened! Or is it? With a steady voice and keen focus, Best examines how a culture develops fears and fantasies and how these visions are created and recreated in every generation. By dismantling current ideas about the future, collective memory, and sociology’s marginalization in the public square, Best sheds light on how social problems—and our anxiety about them—are socially constructed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAnxietyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aamerican dream.  aanxiety.  acollective memory.  adaily apprehension.  adismantling ideas about the future.  aearly retirement.  afantasies.  afears.  agenerations.  agraduate from college.  ahealthcare.  ainsecure social times.  akids not learning.  anet worth.  aown a home.  aschools failing.  asocial institutions.  asocial problems.  asocially constructed problems.  asociology marginalization.  asociology.1 aNichols, Lawrence T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchweingruber, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052029635040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096890540u